#Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
State-of-the-art surveys have been conducted in the area of ML. Their focus have ranged from general use of ML techniques [29] and appli- cation in specific cases, such as automotive [30] and telecommunica- tion [31] to specific aspects of ML, such as understanding how expla- nations are generated from an ML algorithm [32] or ML frameworks [24]. Within the field of SE, surveys have been conducted on the use of AI techniques to support SE activities [15,33]. In addition, an overview of ML testing research is provided by Zhang et al. [34] covering infor- mation about testing properties (correctness, robustness), testing com- ponents (data, ML framework) and testing workflow (generation and evaluation) of ML-based software systems. Felderer et al. [35], provide an additional overview on ML testing that includes background, termi- nology definition and the state of research of data-intensive software systems and their testing practices. The authors [34,35] identified sev- eral challenges, such as the need to cover requirement analysis of ML systems, and proposed opportunities for future research in ML testing. Our work is different from previous literature survey papers in sev- eral ways. To our knowledge, it is the first systematic review on the topic that takes a holistic view and industrial context. As opposed to other works, our review does not focus on one aspect, such as ML test- ing. We discuss a variety of aspects, including ML training and serving infrastructures, that are identified from empirical literature as recurring challenges.

- ## ML
#ML #Workflow #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
ML specific workflows have two distinct major activities of ML model training and inference [5,11]. From these main activities, a nine-staged ML workflow is reported to be used by different development teams at Microsoft and consists of model requirements, data collection, data clean- ing, data labelling, feature engineering, model training, model evaluation, model deployment and model monitoring [11]. Building a supervised ML model involves developing, training, evaluating and modifying ML mod- els using a dataset prepared from a data source. The goal at this phase is to learn from input data and create a suitable model by iteratively estimating, optimising and tuning the parameters of the model.

- ## Safety
#Safety #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
There are huge expectations on AI applications in domain of complex system which operate in complex environment. Many of such systems are safety-critical systems, i.e. systems which in a case of a failure can cause death or serious injury to people, or large economic or environ- mental harm. In this context, safety is defined as ability of a system to ensure avoidance of such harm. A traditional approach in developingL.E. Lwakatare, A. Raj and I. Crnkovic et al. Information and Software Technology 127 (2020) 106368 such systems is to analyse the system run-time context, to identify pos- sible threats, and then justifiable determine the system behavior. When using ML technology, the justifiable prediction of the system is in prin- ciple not possible, as ML models are by their nature statistical (and non- deterministic) models. In this case, an approach similar to that used for software development could be applied – when the system properties cannot be proved, the rigorous and traceable development process can be deployed. These processes are however not developed for AI devel- opment, and this is reflected in a number of challenges the developers meet

- ## Safety
#Safety #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Data acquisition. Safety-critical complex problems, such as au- tonomous driving, often involve large data collection. However, because of an infinite number of possibilities, e.g., different driving scenarios, data collection that fits for all scenarios will not be fully completed [P30]. As a result, the ML models will not have sufficient generaliza- tion ability because of the incompleteness of training data [P32]. Such complex ML problems require not only effective mechanisms to collect data, whose criteria is not merely dataset size but also the anomalies in datasets that are difficult to collect [P30, P38]. Anomalies constituting critical and ambiguous situations where the ML-based system needs to react in a predictably safe manner are difficult to collect because they occur rarely or are dangerous [P30]. Furthermore, creating labels in dataset manually by human judges [P32, P38] is an approach that is expensive, time-consuming and unreliable because of ambiguities and the fact that guidelines are never clear and comprehensive enough to account for all nuances in the dataset [P32, P44]. For instance, when building a conversational in-vehicle digital assistant prototype by [P32], an in-depth manual analysis of over 9000 discussions between customer support representatives and drivers about ADAS was conducted. The lat- ter was done to help the developers to understand the drivers’ needs and identify the main classes useful for classifying the intents of drivers’ speech queries in such a way that there would be precise access to re- quested vehicle information. The classes identified were used by crowd- sources to label training data.

- ## Safety
#Safety #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Training. Developing ADAS system required that sensors and recog- nition algorithms needed to be improved so that they provide more re- liable context information to the ML algorithms [P30]. Furthermore, the lack of a systematic process not only for ML-algorithm evaluation but also for the psychological perception of the changes in behaviours by the driver required that they first are developed [P30]. For safety- critical systems that rely on adaptive and non-deterministic ML models, assuring that safety and reliability are enhanced rather than diminished is a difficult task and one that lacks well-established methods [P33]. Current standards, e.g., ISO 26262, were developed without consider- ing DL and, as such, the present adherence challenges addressing safety assessment [P68].

- ## Safety
#Safety #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Evaluation. Performance evaluations of the ML models do not rep- resent system verification, which ensures system’s reliability against the differences in executions between training and operational environ- ment, among other factors. DL models can impact the safety assessment of ISO 26262 through its non-interpretability [P68]. Similarly, in the fields of industrial automation and medicine, ML techniques are ques- tionable if results are not reproducible or comprehensible by medical ex- perts [P4, P39]. Model explainability is a critical issue especially when DL models or representative learning is used [P45, P42, P43, P53, P56, P64, P68]. Practitioners have proposed an assurance case approach that deconstructs the safety goals of ML-based software system into technical performance requirements on ML functions under explicit consideration of assumptions on the system (and the components within the system context) environment [P68]. However, this approach requires the devel- opment of entirely new verification techniques and the demonstration of its effectiveness [P68].

- ## Privacy
#Privacy #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Privacy is ability to control which information is available and which must be protected for particular category of stakeholder. Many risks are associated with a large collection of sensitive data, which impacts the development of ML component(s). Since ML modelling is based on data, in principle the more data features are used the higher the potential to build better and more accurate models. At the same time, the risk of exposing data to unauthorized persons increases dramatically in comparison to non ML-based systems. This calls for Privacy engineering, which in general is not supported, and for this reason it becomes one of the major challenges in ML-based system development.

- ## Privacy
#Privacy #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Data acquisition. In the development of predictive models involving pharmaceutical companies, data protection policies imposed limitations that were difficult to overcome, such as limited access to training data since it contained structures of confidential compounds [P39]. Similarly, for mobile apps [P6] and online services [P1, P8, P27, P28, P42, P70], privacy information of the users’ brought about the implementation of safeguards that are carefully considered in order to protect users’ pri- vacy and to comply with privacy laws. The approaches range from the anonymization of data identifying individuals [P27, P35, P70] and col- lecting data internally from employees [P8] to using alternative avail- able data, e.g., social network content [P6]. In general, large collections of sensitive data entail great risks [P60].

- ## Privacy
#Privacy #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Training. Private datasets make it difficult for ML engineers to perform initial data exploration since the visual inspection of raw data is often not permitted and data may already have been aggregated [P8, P70]. Data protection laws vary across the world and present challenges by requiring the building of privacy-compliant ML models [P42, P60]. Tech- nical solutions that facilitate remote access to models and their porta- bility to system implementations need to be adopted [P39, P60]. For example, to preserve privacy, federated ML model training is one ap- proach, where a central global ML model is deployed to edge devices for further training on private datasets [P42, P60]. Highly processed and minimally scoped updates from local ML models are then delivered to the central ML model for aggregation [P42, P60]. ML models should be made accessible to local deployments for early testing and evalu- ations [P39]. Federated Learning systems face several practical chal- lenges. Edge devices, e.g., mobile devices, have only sporadic access to power and network connectivity. Thus, the set of locals in the edge par- ticipating in each update step is unpredictable, and the system must be robust for the edge that is dropping out [P60]. As such, one main chal- lenge of federated training is to ensure a secure aggregation of model updates [P60].

- ## Privacy
#Privacy #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Evaluation. Debugging specific scenarios and predictions is very chal- lenging without access to the underlying data [P8]. Practitioners have reported on the need to build ML workflows that allow one to evaluate ML models without being able to visually inspect the underlying data. This will facilitate effective data cleaning and feature identification use- ful to help designers make progress in deploying ML models of private data [P8].

- ## Privacy
#Privacy #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Deployment. According to practitioners’ experience [P42], federated learning requires specialized deployment frameworks capable to handle changes at the edge. ML model training at the edge on mobile devices assumes that all devices are equally likely to participate and complete each round [P48, P60]. However, in practice, the federated training ap- proach potentially introduces bias in that devices only train when they are on a connected network and charging [P60]. In some countries, the majority of people rarely have access to an unmetered network. Also, deployment may be limited to particular devices, e.g., phones with cer- tain Android versions and at least 2 GB of memory, which forms a source of potential bias [P60].

Privacy main challenges: limited access to training data, difficult data exploration in private datasets, building of privacy-compliant ML models, need for secure aggregation of model updates and difficul- ties with training at the edge. Main solutions employed is federated learning.

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
ML components of large and complex systems deal with issues con- cerning the scaling of data, ML model size, and the number of ML mod- els.

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Data acquisition. Despite large data availability, cold start and sparse data problem is dominant in large scale online services. For ML compo- nents, this means there are very limited amounts of training data avail- able for the item(s) of interest, for instance to make recommendations [P1, P2, P3, P5, P7, P8, P10, P11, P13]. As a result, it becomes difficult to process the items and train accurate ML models due to problems of data imbalance, for example. The cold start and the sparse data prob- lem are often because of fresh content having low user interaction in the large scale online services [P7, P9, P10, P25], short item life-span in consumer-to-consumer (C2C) e-commerce services [P2, P3, P28] and data heterogeneity e.g., retailers with varying product catalogues for tar- geted ad display [P1, P21, P22, P23]. These problems are in addition to noisy and poor data structures with lacking taxonomy for metadata as- sociated with user content [P3, P7]. Furthermore, getting feature values in real-time is difficult because the data is often distributed, synthesised and requiring aggregation before use [P22]. Generally, large data col- lection does not necessarily translate into a large availability of training data [P7].

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Training. Large ML models, including wide and deep neural networks [P5], are difficult and time-consuming to train on a single machine even though they have high accuracy [P18]. Thus, distributed algorithm training on numerous machines is often employed to reduce the train- ing latency and time needed for convergence [P20, P24, P40, P48, P69, P70]. Current approaches for distributed DL model training have trade- offs [P11, P24] and involve splitting the whole neural network graph into many sub-graphs to be trained in parallel on multiple machines [P10, P18, P50, P69], explicitly 100 GPUs in [P2]. Distributed algorithm training through the partitioning of the neural network is reported to in- troduce communication, synchronization and memory challenges [P20, P50] due to the partitioning of neural network graph [P13]. The bene- fits from an alternative approach (i.e., data parallelism) are reported to diminish when the network bandwidth is too low, such that performing parameter synchronization takes longer than the gradient computations [P20]. According to the authors, the ability to scale linearly is related to both the model size and the bandwidth size, for which training quality is impacted by trade-offs in synchronization, consistency, and perfor- mance [P20]. For companies, distributed algorithm training approaches are an ongoing research area because there are various optimization techniques [P13, P20, P24]. Achieving distributed ML/DL model train- ing requires a high-performance resource and training job orchestration system capable to effectively and efficiently reduce communication and memory cost, among others [P57, P59].

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Every time a new set of training data arrives, the ML models need to be retrained [P1, P5, P20, P43]. Continuous and frequent retraining of ML models from scratch, for example daily, is computationally expensive, complicates parameter tuning and delays the time for deploying an up- dated ML model [P1, P5, P9, P15, P18, P21, P28, P36, P43, P64]. To avoid training from scratch every time, techniques that leverage previ- ous models need to be used [P1, P5], for instance incremental training in [P1, P18, P28, P35]. In [P5], practitioners implemented a ‘warm- starting system’ that initialises the new model with the neural network embedding and weights from the previous model.

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Deployment. Most ML-based systems have stringent latency require- ments at ML model inference stage [P1, P3, P10, P17, P18, P26, P32, P36, P38, P40, P42]. Strict service level agreements (SLAs) require timely and proper content to be delivered to users, such as in item rec- ommendations and targeted ad display [P3, P20, P22, P51]. These chal- lenge efficient and specialized design of ML serving infrastructure, which needs to serve many user requests [P5, P8, P9, P26], e.g. hundreds of millions of requests per day for online services [P1, P3, P7]. To cope with low latency and high throughput, some ML systems were designed to do much of the computation offline and only very lightweight computa- tion at serving time [P1, P9]. This means that the serving infrastructure is optimized for batch-updates as opposed to real-time updates of ML models [P1]. Offline computation for batch-updates significantly slow development velocity and any changes to model require re-computation of all queries offline making it a time-consuming process [P9]. As such, evolution is observed from batch-updates to real-time computation and model serving [P9, P11]. Online/incremental learning [P28], wherein an ML model is first trained with a subset of data and is later fine- tuned with new data incrementally [P18, P21] is also used. According to Google practitioners, ML serving infrastructure is often designed using ad-hoc and non-reusable solutions [P63, P64]. For example, ML mod- els are kept in a BigTable, and a simple server code loads and handles requests to the models from there [P63]. The result is that complex- ity accumulates and support is needed for model versioning (for roll- back option), multiple models (for A/B testing) [P63]. Overall the latter necessitates careful management of ML serving infrastructure to avoid availability lapses and performance problems from latency spikes among others [P63, P64].

- ## Scalability
#Scalability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Scalability main challenges: cold start and sparse data problem, tradeoffs with distributed ML model, balancing efficiency and ef- fectiveness in ML workflow, continuous and frequent retraining of ML models, difficult ML diagnosis and difficulties in designing serv- ing infrastructure. Main solutions employed: transfer learning, and development of distributed ML frameworks and development plat- forms.

- ## Adaptability
#Adaptability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Feature engineering is considered an important and labour intensive task, even when neural networks are used [P1, P4, P7, P8, P12, P19, P21, P25, P26, P27, P29, P45]. Difficulties in feature engineering are due to the fact that raw input data cannot be readily applied to ML algorithm [P7, P12, P27, P45, P71] thereby requiring pre-processing. Also, fea- tures can be heterogeneous compared to traditional image applications [P8]. In addition, determining how features are related to predictions especially from temporal user action data is reported to be challeng- ing [P7, P9, P21]. Lack of a simplified and well-defined procedure for adding new features, for example after determining that the previous ML model had relied on data deemed useful for business logic but not ML, is problematic [P12, P26] and sometimes expensive [P17]. Also rel- evant when the initial ML model may have been formulated to operate on periodic data to generate predictions in batch rather than operate on the real-time data [P11], which sets its own constraints.L.E. Lwakatare, A. Raj and I. Crnkovic et al. Information and Software Technology 127 (2020) 106368 Limitations in ML pipeline and infrastructure lead to development of custom tools in order to successfully apply ML algorithms, particu- larly when there is limited support for ML frameworks in certain pro- gramming languages [P12]. Uncontrolled model training experimentation occurs when designers use ad-hoc approaches during ML model build- ing and selection [P9, P12, P55, P61, P66, P70, P71]. This can results in ‘pipeline jungles and glue-code’, wherein the supporting code is written to feed data into and out of the ML frameworks [P43]. As a consequence, the problem of ‘dead experimental code paths’ is reported whereby the designers tend to branch off from the main production code to perform short-term experiments with alternative ML frameworks [P43]. In doing so they introduce maintenance problems because of it can be difficult to facilitate backward compatibility [P22, P43]. In addition, ad-hoc ap- proaches during ML model experiment makes it difficult to effectively train, compare and quickly repeat the different model training results [P12, P43, P55], particularly when designers are continually training a large number of ML modes [P22]

- ## Adaptability
#Adaptability #Model #Development #Machine #Learning #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
Adaptability (ability of a system to accommodate to changes) was identified as an important and challenging aspect in ML system devel- opment, due to sensitivity of ML component to input data. The develop- ment of ML components of large and complex software systems should not only be able to adapt to the evolutionary changes in the system, but also to the changes of the run-time context. This is reflected in all phases of the ML development workflow.

- ## Adaptability

Data acquisition. The main challenge related to data acquisition is related to unstable data dependencies and data quality problems. Changes from an evolving system may alter or introduce new sources of training data for ML component, whose development pipeline must ensure high quality training data from the input data for a reliable system [P9, P11, P12, P22, P23, P42, P43, P45, P47, P67, P65]. The input data is large and can be generated by joining heterogeneous data sources that have different data qualities and trust issues [P9, P34, P40, P45, P70]. Since a ML component is dependent on data, changes in the distribution of in- put data used for creating training data can slowly degrade the overall performance of the deployed ML component [P45, P66, P67]. Such an unstable data dependency is especially problematic when the ML compo- nent incorporates portions of data from sources that are either partially or entirely outside of the development team’s control as the changes can go undetected [P9, P22, P67]. The building of high-quality, unbi- ased training data from the raw input data is generally non-trivial [P12, P36] and is often challenged by limitations in data collection, cleaning and transformation [P2, P3, P4, P8, P9, P12, P19, P35, P36, P45, P46, P64].

Training. Training an ML model requires a precise formulation of ML problem that would depict complex relationships between features (in- put variables to ML algorithm) and predictions [P4,P9]. Typically, once a user has specified a problem, it needs to be conceptualized and for- malized especially since the user often presents it informally [P4]. Ac- cording to [P4], it is not always obvious how to map user specified prob- lem to a learning problem. Often, early assumptions during ML model building lead to naïve approaches applied to rather complex ML problems [P4, P11, P12, P14, P15, P16, P27, P33, P34, P42]. Further, a naïve ML problem formulation results in sub-optimal solution [P18, P21, P23]. To avoid the latter, in [P14] a cost-benefit analysis of automatically sending notification emails by the LinkedIn service was first empirically evalu- ated with end-users before training an ML model. The purpose of ML component was to optimise the number of emails to be sent for each individual user [P14]. The cost-benefit analysis enabled developers to better formulate the problem that considers the trade-off points involv- ing the positive and negative outcomes of sending notification emails [P14, P16]. In other cases, conceptualization of ML problem requires adaptation of learning algorithm, including also new definition of what the target feature means [P4].

Evaluation. Traditional (offline) ML metrics that are used to evaluate performance of ML models during experiments are reported to be insuf- ficient and too narrow. This is because they do not reflect the overall performance of the system in production, wherein business impact can also be evaluated [P1, P5, P6, P7, P9, P12, P14, P21, P22, P25, P64, P65]. In practice, achieving a business goal, e.g., improving the conver- sion rate within the targeted population [P16] is rather important than a mere maximization of accuracy of an ML model [P6, P23]. This is in addition to active participation of users in development of ML system [P04]. Users can be useful to establish the evaluation criteria, and typi- cally must be convinced to use the results of ML models [P04]. Accord- ing to the above definition the user must not only be present, but also actively participate in the development of a “real-world” application. In fraud/anomaly detection, traditional metrics can be less important and spending more time on model refinement can delay detection and response, causing the damage to accumulate quickly [P26, P29]. Un- less traditional ML metrics, e.g., precision and recall, are adjusted, one can fail to identify fraudulent behaviour that can lead to financial loss [P29]. The selection of the other metrics is also difficult and expensive to employ in other domains like automotive [P31, P32]. In [P16], an engagement metric is re-evaluated since it is not attributable solely to sending email notifications and gives a narrow view to an ecosystem of networked services consisting of several system components. Traditional ML metrics are computed offline to guide the iterative improvements to the ML system [P9], but the final determination of ML model effective- ness needs to rely on other metrics in production [P7, P15, P31].

Deployment. Deviations in data (or feature) distribution between the training data and the serving data result in sub-optimal, inconsistent ML model performance because of the skew [P8, P9, P12, P43, P45, P64, P65, P67]. New data collection [P12] and unstable data dependencies [P45] can introduce serving bias when care is not taken during the de- velopment of the ML component. Locating the list of transformations during data acquisition and applying the same set of transformations in the data extraction pipeline can impose significant maintenance ef- fort [P8]. When gathering new training data from the prediction service [P8], it is observed that a deployed ML model impacts the training data of future ML models because it may introduce a direct feedback loop to the training data, making it difficult to outperform the previously de- ployed ML model [P9]. As such, the training data needs to be isolated from the influence of the previously deployed ML model.

Adaptability main challenges: unstable data dependencies and qual- ity problems, naïve ML problem formulation, difficult feature engi- neering, uncontrolled ML model training experimentation, narrow evaluation metrices and training-serving skew. Main solutions em- ployed: data validation automation, tracking metadata in the ML model experiments, test and deployment heuristics for ML-based sys- tem and online A/B ML model experiment.

- ## Interplay
#Interplay #SEAI #Engineering #Process #Software #Engineering #ResearchStreams #AI #Engineering 
From a process perspective, the interplay between traditional SE pro- cess activities and ML workflow activities is not well reported. Murphy et al. [19] report that traditional software testing processes are chal- lenging to apply because of the absence of a reliable test-oracle and, as a result, a new testing approach is proposed. The new approach involves the creation of test cases to analyse: (i) the problem domain and its corre- sponding real-world data set, (ii) the ML algorithm and (iii) ML application run-time options. Some limitations to this approach are that it is difficult to apply to non-linear models, such as neural networks in Deep learn- ing (DL). Model understanding is a critical issue when DL algorithms are used because of limited explainability and their vulnerability to ad- versarial attacks making this area an active subject of research to date [25,26].
